Below is a full PRD + stack spec for VirtualPC, written so a strong coding agent can build an MVP-to-v1 in one repo without assuming AWS or any managed cloud. The design is explicitly self-hosted, open-source-first, and optimized for Linux bare metal or your own rented servers. The critical runtime choice is Firecracker microVMs for the outer machine boundary, because Firecracker is an open-source VMM built on Linux KVM and is designed to create lightweight microVMs with reduced attack surface; it does require Linux KVM and hardware virtualization or nested virtualization. For orchestration, K3s is a practical self-hosted control plane because it is a lightweight CNCF-certified Kubernetes distribution shipped as a small single binary with sqlite as the default datastore.  ￼

VirtualPC PRD

One-line product

VirtualPC is a self-hosted control plane for AI-operated virtual computers.
Each job gets a real isolated machine abstraction with terminal, filesystem, browser, apps, and the ability to run nested service containers. Agents work in short verified loops and persist state outside model context.

Product goals

Build a system where an agent can:
	•	boot a fresh PC-like environment
	•	inspect and edit files
	•	browse the web and operate apps
	•	start project services inside nested containers
	•	checkpoint, resume, branch, and replay work
	•	pass tasks only when external verification says they passed

Non-goals for v1

Do not build:
	•	Windows guest support
	•	GPU passthrough into guest VMs
	•	full VDI / remote desktop product parity
	•	general marketplace / billing / public SaaS
	•	internet-facing multitenancy with weak isolation

⸻

Product principles

1. Machine-first, not tool-first

The agent should feel like it has a workstation, not just a repo container.

2. Outer isolation is VM, inner isolation is container

Use a microVM as the security boundary. Inside it, run project containers for app/db/worker workloads.

3. Short loops, durable memory

Use Ralph-style bounded iterations:
	•	load task card
	•	act
	•	verify
	•	persist progress
	•	retry or finish

4. External truth

No task is “done” because the worker says so. A verifier must prove it with tests, assertions, or screenshots.

5. Self-hosted by default

No AWS assumptions. All core services must run on:
	•	one Linux workstation for dev
	•	one Linux server for staging
	•	3+ Linux nodes for production

⸻

Recommended stack

Host / infra
	•	Ubuntu Server 24.04 LTS on bare metal or dedicated VM hosts
	•	KVM enabled in BIOS/UEFI
	•	Firecracker for microVMs
	•	containerd on hosts
	•	K3s for cluster orchestration
	•	CNI: Cilium or Flannel initially
	•	Ingress: Traefik or Nginx Ingress

Why:
	•	Firecracker gives the strongest self-hosted machine abstraction for this use case.  ￼
	•	containerd is a standard runtime and supports multiple runtimes.  ￼
	•	K3s keeps operations simple for a private cluster.  ￼

Core control-plane backend
	•	Language: Go
	•	API: gRPC internally, REST externally
	•	Workflow engine: Temporal
	•	Event bus: NATS + JetStream
	•	Primary DB: PostgreSQL
	•	Cache / queue / ephemeral state: Valkey
	•	Object storage: MinIO
	•	Search / analytics (optional v1.1): OpenSearch

Why:
	•	Temporal is open source and built for durable execution and resumable workflows.  ￼
	•	NATS is a lightweight open-source messaging system; JetStream adds persistence and replay.  ￼
	•	PostgreSQL is a mature open-source object-relational database.  ￼
	•	Valkey is open source under BSD and works well for cache, streams, and broker-like use cases.  ￼
	•	MinIO is S3-compatible and self-hostable; the upstream server repo is AGPLv3, so that license needs to be acceptable to you.  ￼

Agent runtime / model serving
	•	Model gateway: LiteLLM
	•	Primary local inference: vLLM for hosted OSS models
	•	Secondary local inference / laptop mode: Ollama
	•	Embeddings: same vLLM cluster or dedicated embedding service
	•	Optional external providers: through LiteLLM only

Why:
	•	LiteLLM gives a unified gateway and OpenAI-compatible proxy behavior.  ￼
	•	vLLM exposes an OpenAI-compatible server and is built for fast inference/serving.  ￼
	•	Ollama is convenient for local-only single-machine installs.  ￼

Browser / UI automation
	•	Playwright
	•	Chromium in guest images
	•	optional noVNC or Apache Guacamole for remote visual inspection

Playwright is a solid fit because it supports Chromium, Firefox, and WebKit, runs headless or headed, and includes auto-waiting and assertions that reduce flaky UI automation.  ￼

Observability
	•	OpenTelemetry
	•	Prometheus
	•	Grafana
	•	Loki
	•	Tempo optional if you want Grafana-native traces instead of another backend

OpenTelemetry gives vendor-neutral traces/metrics/logs instrumentation; Prometheus covers metrics; Loki gives log aggregation with low-cost metadata indexing.  ￼

Frontend
	•	Next.js
	•	TypeScript
	•	Tailwind
	•	shadcn/ui
	•	xterm.js for terminal
	•	Monaco for code editing
	•	React Query / TanStack Query
	•	Zustand for local UI state

This part is a product choice, not a standards claim. It is simply the fastest clean stack for an internal-control-plane UI.

⸻

Architecture

Top-level services
	1.	api-gateway
	2.	auth-service
	3.	project-service
	4.	task-service
	5.	computer-service
	6.	snapshot-service
	7.	artifact-service
	8.	policy-service
	9.	agent-orchestrator
	10.	verifier-service
	11.	browser-service
	12.	model-gateway
	13.	event-relay
	14.	telemetry-collector

Runtime layers

Layer 0: physical or rented Linux hosts

Runs:
	•	K3s node agents
	•	Firecracker
	•	containerd
	•	bridge networking
	•	storage mounts

Layer 1: VirtualPC microVM

Each VirtualPC is a Firecracker microVM with:
	•	Linux guest OS
	•	agent sidecar
	•	browser
	•	shell
	•	docker or nerdctl/containerd inside guest
	•	workspace disk
	•	capability daemon
	•	telemetry agent

Layer 2: nested workloads inside the VirtualPC

For project services:
	•	db container
	•	backend container
	•	worker container
	•	test runner container

Layer 3: child VirtualPCs

Used for:
	•	branch experiments
	•	risky code execution
	•	QA runs
	•	parallel subtasks

⸻

Deployment topologies

Dev: single machine

For one developer:
	•	1 Linux host
	•	K3s single-node
	•	PostgreSQL
	•	Temporal
	•	NATS
	•	Valkey
	•	MinIO
	•	LiteLLM
	•	optional Ollama
	•	Firecracker workers on same host

Use this to build the product itself.

Staging: single stronger server

For a small team:
	•	1 dedicated bare-metal server
	•	same stack
	•	10–30 concurrent VirtualPCs
	•	nightly cleanup
	•	snapshots to local MinIO

Production: 3 control nodes + N worker nodes
	•	3 K3s server nodes
	•	N worker nodes with KVM
	•	separate storage disks
	•	MinIO distributed mode
	•	PostgreSQL HA optional
	•	Temporal on dedicated namespace
	•	model-serving nodes separate from VM worker nodes

