⸻

Capability model

Every VirtualPC gets a capability manifest.

Example:

{
  "shell": true,
  "filesystem": {
    "read": ["/workspace", "/tmp"],
    "write": ["/workspace", "/tmp"]
  },
  "browser": true,
  "git": true,
  "docker_inside_guest": true,
  "allowed_container_registries": ["docker.io/library", "ghcr.io/your-org"],
  "network": {
    "egress_mode": "allowlist",
    "allowed_domains": ["github.com", "npmjs.org", "pypi.org"]
  },
  "secrets": {
    "mountable": ["github_token", "npm_token"],
    "export_to_shell": false
  }
}


⸻

Security model

Host isolation

Use microVMs, not plain containers, for agent workspaces. Firecracker’s model is intentionally minimal to reduce attack surface.  ￼

Guest isolation

Inside the guest:
	•	nested app containers use containerd
	•	optional gVisor runtime class for untrusted nested containers
	•	read-only base rootfs
	•	writable overlay/workspace disk
	•	cgroup quotas
	•	seccomp
	•	no privileged containers unless explicitly allowed

gVisor is useful where you want an extra sandbox around nested containers because it virtualizes the system interfaces usually implemented by the host kernel through a per-sandbox application kernel.  ￼

Network policy

Modes:
	•	offline
	•	package-only
	•	allowlist
	•	full-egress
	•	internal-cluster-only

Secret handling
	•	secrets never persisted inside snapshots by default
	•	inject at runtime via tmpfs mount
	•	redact from logs
	•	rotate task-scoped credentials
	•	one secret scope per project/environment

Auditing

Store:
	•	action logs
	•	API calls
	•	prompt hashes
	•	command transcripts
	•	network session metadata
	•	snapshot lineage

