Use Valkey only for ephemeral state and fast coordination, not source of truth.

⸻

Verification spec format

Each task stores a machine-readable verifier spec.

Example:

{
  "checks": [
    {
      "type": "shell",
      "command": "cd /workspace/repo && pnpm test -- --runInBand",
      "success_exit_code": 0
    },
    {
      "type": "http",
      "url": "http://127.0.0.1:3000/health",
      "status": 200
    },
    {
      "type": "playwright",
      "script": "tests/e2e/login.spec.ts",
      "expectations": [
        "dashboard visible",
        "no console errors"
      ]
    }
  ]
}

Supported verifier types in v1
	•	shell
	•	unit
	•	integration
	•	http
	•	playwright
	•	file existence
	•	JSON schema
	•	screenshot compare

⸻

Snapshot and branching model

Snapshot types
	•	pre-task
	•	post-task
	•	scheduled
	•	manual
	•	pre-upgrade
	•	pre-verify

What a snapshot contains
	•	guest image ref
	•	workspace volume snapshot
	•	nested container manifests
	•	task metadata
	•	file diff summary
	•	package manifest
	•	browser profile optional

Branching

You should support:
	•	fork from latest snapshot into child VirtualPC
	•	attach same project context
	•	isolate secrets and network policies
	•	record lineage

This enables “try two fixes in parallel” safely.

⸻

Model orchestration design

Model classes
	•	planner-large
	•	operator-coder
	•	operator-browser
	•	verifier-critic
	•	recovery-cheap

Routing

Use LiteLLM as the stable API.
Backends:
	•	local vLLM for main open models
	•	Ollama for single-host installs
	•	optional remote provider through LiteLLM

Prompt/memory package

Every iteration should include:
	•	task card
	•	acceptance criteria
	•	compact project architecture summary
	•	last iteration result
	•	latest verifier output
	•	current repo diff summary
	•	available capabilities
	•	budget remaining
	•	safety/policy constraints

Never dump raw full history if avoidable.

