⸻

Suggested implementation decisions

Why Go for the backend

Because the core services are orchestration-heavy and concurrency-heavy:
	•	long-running workflows
	•	gRPC
	•	host agents
	•	websockets
	•	streaming logs
	•	resource controllers

Why not make everything Python

Python is fine for agents and verifier helpers, but I would keep the control plane in Go and use Python only where model/tooling ecosystems help.

Why not use full Kubernetes inside every VM

Because that is too heavy for the first serious version. Use:
	•	K3s outside
	•	containerd/Docker inside the guest
	•	plain compose-like orchestration inside the guest

Why not pure Docker-in-Docker as the machine

Because your whole product thesis is “agent gets a computer.” A microVM fits that thesis and the security model better.

⸻

Runtime profiles

dev-browser
	•	2 vCPU
	•	4 GB RAM
	•	20 GB disk
	•	Chromium
	•	Playwright
	•	Node/Python
	•	Docker in guest enabled

fullstack-app
	•	4 vCPU
	•	8 GB RAM
	•	40 GB disk
	•	browser enabled
	•	Docker in guest enabled
	•	test tools preinstalled

data-worker
	•	4 vCPU
	•	16 GB RAM
	•	100 GB disk
	•	no browser
	•	Python/data libs
	•	restricted egress

secure-untrusted
	•	2 vCPU
	•	4 GB RAM
	•	20 GB disk
	•	no secrets
	•	offline or allowlist only
	•	nested containers through gVisor if enabled

⸻

Example end-to-end user flow

User asks:
“Create a SaaS dashboard app with auth, postgres, background jobs, and tests.”

System flow:
	1.	Planner creates PRD and task DAG
	2.	Allocator creates one fullstack-app VirtualPC
	3.	Operator clones or initializes repo
	4.	Operator starts nested postgres and redis containers
	5.	Operator scaffolds app
	6.	Operator runs migrations
	7.	Operator launches app
	8.	Verifier runs:
	•	unit tests
	•	health endpoint check
	•	Playwright login flow
	9.	On failure, recovery agent forks a child VM from latest snapshot
	10.	Best branch is merged back by patch or git cherry-pick
	11.	Artifacts and replay trace are stored

⸻

NFRs

Performance
	•	cold VM boot target: under 5 seconds for warmed templates, under 15 seconds for cold templates
	•	task scheduling latency: under 2 seconds
	•	terminal round-trip: under 250 ms on LAN
	•	screenshot capture: under 2 seconds

Reliability
	•	no task state loss on orchestrator restart
	•	iterations resumable after service crash
	•	all state transitions idempotent

Temporal is a good fit here specifically because it is designed for durable execution and resume-after-failure behavior.  ￼

Security
	•	no privileged guest access to host
	•	secrets excluded from snapshots by default
	•	per-project egress policy
	•	immutable audit log for sensitive actions

Observability
	•	per-task trace id
	•	per-computer metrics
	•	per-iteration logs
	•	correlated verifier run logs

OpenTelemetry + Prometheus + Loki is a sensible open stack for this.  ￼

⸻

Acceptance criteria for v1

A build is “v1 complete” when all are true:
	1.	User can self-host the entire stack on Linux with no managed cloud dependency.
	2.	User can create a project and launch a VirtualPC from the web UI.
	3.	Agent can execute at least one bounded task loop inside the VirtualPC.
	4.	Agent can start nested containers inside the guest for app/db/worker.
	5.	Verifier can prove success via shell + HTTP + Playwright.
	6.	System can create a snapshot and fork a child VirtualPC from it.
	7.	UI can replay iterations with logs, diffs, and screenshots.
	8.	Policies can restrict egress and secret injection.
	9.	System metrics, traces, and logs are visible in observability dashboards.
	10.	The whole stack can be started from documented scripts and manifests.

⸻

